@EndNode

@Node "Source_code" "term.guide/Source code"
@Next "Program updates"
@Prev "Acknowledgements"
@Toc "Main"

@{u}@{b}Source code@{uu}@{ub}

   Since there are still only very few well-documented examples (or
general programming examples) for Kickstart 2.x and Kickstart 3.x I
have decided to include the full `C' source code with the `term'
distribution.

   The source code is @{b}not@{ub} intended for commercial use. If you are about
to include portions in commercial programs you will need to ask me for
permission. Still you may use parts of the source code for
non-commercial software development without my consent.

   I sincerely hope that the release of the full `term' source code will
give Kickstart 2.x a better start (I've overcome quite a lot of
obstacles) so that more programs to use the new OS features will be
available soon.


@EndNode

@Node "Program_updates" "term.guide/Program updates"
@Next "Documentation and online help"
@Prev "Source code"
@Toc "Main"

@{u}@{b}Program updates@{uu}@{ub}

   Whenever a new release of `term' becomes available I will try to
make it known in the telecommunications networks. To order a copy send
a self addressed envelope, the equivalent to DM 7,- (cash or cheque)
and two 3.5" double density disks/one 3.5" high density disk to the
author.

   The most current `term' release will be available through ftp from
@{b}ftp.informatik.uni-oldenburg.de@{ub} (@{b}134.106.1.9@{ub}), look into the
@{b}/pub/amiga/term@{ub} directory.

   New program releases will be announced in the @{b}comp.sys.amiga.data@{ub}
newsgroup.


@EndNode

@Node "Documentation_and_online_help" "term.guide/Documentation and online help"
@Next "Operating the program"
@Prev "Program updates"
@Toc "Main"

@{u}@{b}Documentation and online help@{uu}@{ub}

   `term' comes bundled with a number of documentation files, these are:

@{b}term.doc@{ub}
     Human-readable english program documentation in standard ASCII
     format.

@{b}term.dvi@{ub}
     English program documentation in a format suitable for printing
     using a utility to print TeX-DVI-output files, such as supplied
     with the packages AmigaTeX(tm) or PasTeX.

@{b}term.guide@{ub}
     English program documentation in AmigaGuide(tm) format suitable to
     submit to @{b}AmigaGuide@{ub} or @{b}MultiView@{ub}.

@{b}termRexx.doc@{ub}
     Human-readable english `term' ARexx interface documentation in
     standard ASCII format. This file describes all the ARexx host
     commands `term' supports and also gives a brief introduction how
     to use them.

@{b}termRexx.dvi@{ub}
     English ARexx interface documentation in a format suitable to
     printing using a utility to print TeX-DVI-output files, such as
     supplied with the packages AmigaTeX(tm) or PasTeX. @{b}Note that in
     order to print this manual the LaTeX font @{b}circle10@{ub} is required@{ub}

@{b}termRexx.guide@{ub}
     English ARexx interface documentation in AmigaGuide(tm) format
     suitable to submit to @{b}AmigaGuide@{ub} or @{b}MultiView@{ub}.

@{b}xprascii.doc ... xprzmodem.doc@{ub}
     Human-readable documentation on the XPR transfer libraries
     supplied with `term'.

   In order to take advantage of the online-help feature, Kickstart 3.0
and the file @{b}term.guide@{ub} are required. Copy the file to the drawer the
`term' main program is located in and configure the @{b}`term' help text
file@{ub} settings (see @{"Path panel" Link "Path_panel"}) to point to @{b}PROGDIR:term.guide@{ub}. Once
this has been done, pressing the @{b}Help@{ub} key in any window to support
online help will bring up context sensitive online help.


@EndNode

@Node "Operating_the_program" "term.guide/Operating the program"
@Next "Workbench and Shell"
@Prev "Documentation and online help"
@Toc "Main"

@{u}@{b}Operating the program@{uu}@{ub}

   `term' can be controlled both by mouse and keyboard. With very few
exceptions each operation requiring mouse control can also be executed
using keyboard shortcuts.

   The program can be started both from Workbench and from Shell.
Kickstart 2.04 (revision 37.175) and Workbench 2.04 (revision 37.67) are
required to run `term'.


@EndNode

@Node "Workbench_and_Shell" "term.guide/Workbench and Shell"
@Next "Keyboard control"
@Prev "Operating the program"
@Toc "Main"

@{u}@{b}Workbench and Shell@{uu}@{ub}

   The `behaviour' of `term' can be changed by adding tool type entries
to the corresponding Workbench icon or by specifying additional command
line parameters when running the program from the Shell. Supported
keywords are:

@{b}WINDOW@{ub}
     The console window specifier to be used when opening terminal
     output windows (this will override the default settings). The
     default is @{b}CON:0/11//100/term Output Window/CLOSE/SCREEN TERM@{ub}.

@{b}PUBSCREEN@{ub}
     The name of a public screen to open the `term' window on. In case
     the public screen happens to be unavailable, `term' will fall back
     to the Workbench screen. Note that `term' assumes that the main
     window is to be opened on a public screen rather than on a custom
     screen if this option is in effect, regardless how the default
     settings may be configured.

@{b}STARTUP@{ub}
     The name of an ARexx script file to be run on program startup.

@{b}PORTNAME@{ub}
     The ARexx host port name `term' is to use instead of the built-in
     default name. The port name will be translated to upper case
     characters as required by the ARexx host port naming convention.
     The resulting name must be unique or `term' will fall back to its
     built-in default name.

@{b}SETTINGS@{ub}
     This keyword determines where to read the default configuration
     file from. In order to read it from @{b}Work:term/config@{ub}, one would use
     @{b}term Settings Work:term/config@{ub} from Shell or add the tooltype
     entry @{b}SETTINGS=Work:term/config@{ub} from Workbench. This argument does
     not necessarily give the name of a path to search, but can also
     specify the name of the configuration file to be used.

@{b}UNIT@{ub}
     Similar to the @{b}DEVICE@{ub} keyword the @{b}UNIT@{ub} keywords affects the serial
     driver settings. It determines which serial driver unit is to be
     used instead of the one specified in the default configuration
     file. In order to use unit number 4 one would use @{b}term Unit 4@{ub} from
     Shell or add the tooltype entry @{b}UNIT=4@{ub} from Workbench.

@{b}DEVICE@{ub}
     In order to use a different serial device driver than the one
     specified in the default configuration file, use this keyword. To
     use @{b}duart.device@{ub} one would use @{b}term Device duart.device@{ub} from Shell
     or add the tooltype entry @{b}DEVICE=duart.device@{ub} from Workbench.

@{b}SYNC (Shell only)@{ub}
     If called from Shell `term' will detach itself immediately
     allowing the Shell window to be closed afterwards. This effect can
     be avoided if @{b}SYNC@{ub} is entered in the command line.

@{b}NEW (Shell only)@{ub}
     Usually, running `term' twice will cause the screen of the other
     program to be popped to the front instead of creating a second
     `term' process. To avoid this effect, enter @{b}NEW@{ub} as a calling
     parameter. If called from Workbench, each program will run as a
     separate process.


@EndNode

@Node "Keyboard_control" "term.guide/Keyboard control"
@Next "Screen"
@Prev "Workbench and Shell"
@Toc "Main"

@{u}@{b}Keyboard control@{uu}@{ub}

   Starting with revision 2.2 almost any action can be executed both by
mouse and by keyboard. Each element of the user interface in whose
title an underlined character can be found can be controlled or
activated by pressing the corresponding key. If the object in question
is a list view or scroll bar, pressing the key along with a @{b}Shift@{ub} key
will scroll the list/bar back and forth. Pressing the @{b}Tab@{ub} key will
activate the first string gadget on the screen.


@EndNode

@Node "Screen" "term.guide/Screen"
@Next "Menus"
@Prev "Keyboard control"
@Toc "Main"

@{u}@{b}Screen@{uu}@{ub}

   Unless configured to open only a simple window on a public screen the
`term' main screen will alway open to the full text-overscan size (which
can be set using the @{b}Overscan@{ub} tool in the @{b}Prefs@{ub} drawer).

   At the bottom of the screen a small window displays a few basic
parameters. These are:

@{b}Status@{ub}
     The current program operating status. This includes `Ready',
     `Holding' (@{b}Control + S@{ub} was pressed), `Dialing' (the dialing
     function is at work), `Upload' (data is being sent), `Download'
     (data is being received), `Breaking' (a break signal is
     transmitted across the serial line) and `Hanging up' (connection
     is being cancelled).

@{b}Font@{ub}
     The currently active screen font used for text/graphics rendering.

@{b}Protocol@{ub}
     The currently set data transfer protocol.

@{b}Emulation@{ub}
     The currently active terminal emulation mode.

@{b}Baud rate@{ub}
     The data transfer rate in bits per second.

@{b}Parameters@{ub}
     The current serial parameters (Data bits-Parity-Stop bits).

@{b}Time@{ub}
     The current time of day.

@{b}Online@{ub}
     The time elapsed after a connection was successfully established.
     This counter will be stopped as soon as the connection is
     cancelled (e.g. by hanging up) and is reset to 00:00:00 as soon as
     a new connection is made.

     Every five seconds the time display will change to a calling fee
     display and the other way round.

   The screen itself is opened as a public screen (called @{b}TERM@{ub}) which
is available to other programs for their purposes. If more than one
`term' process is running, the public screen name will change according
to the number of the program (i.e. the first `term' to be started will
call the scren @{b}TERM@{ub}, the second one will call it @{b}TERM.1@{ub}, the third one
@{b}TERM.2@{ub}, etc.). The screen title bar will also display the name of
the public screen.


@EndNode

@Node "Menus" "term.guide/Menus"
@Next "Control panels"
@Prev "Screen"
@Toc "Main"

@{u}@{b}Menus@{uu}@{ub}

   For each requester and input window there exists a set of menu items
to execute the commands associated with the buttons, dials and gauges in
the requester/window. Press the right mouse button to have a look at
the commands and their shortcuts.

   The following text is to describe the menu items available in the
`term' main menu.


 @{" Project " Link "Project"}   Printing, log files, iconification, program termination
 @{" Edit " Link "Edit"}      Clipboard support
 @{" Commands " Link "Commands"}  ARexx- and AmigaDOS command execution
 @{" Phone " Link "Phone"}     Modem and dialing functions
 @{" Transfer " Link "Transfer"}  File transfer functions
 @{" Buffer " Link "Buffer"}    Text buffer functions
 @{" Terminal " Link "Terminal"}  Terminal emulation control
 @{" Settings " Link "Settings"}  Program settings control
 @{" Windows " Link "Windows"}   Auxilary windows


@EndNode

@Node "Project" "term.guide/Project"
@Next "Edit"
@Prev "Menus"
@Toc "Menus"

@{u}Project@{uu}

@{b}Save screen as Picture/Text@{ub}
     This menu serves to save the current terminal window contents
     either as plain ASCII text file or as a picture file.

@{b}Print Screen/Clipboard@{ub}
     These menu entries are to output text on the printer. You can
     either print the contents of the main screen or the contents of
     the clipboard.

@{b}Capture to File/Printer@{ub}
     Selecting one of these menu entries will toggle capturing incoming
     text to the printer and/or a file on disk.

@{b}Iconify@{ub}
     Closes all screens and windows `term' has currently open, resets
     and releases the serial driver and puts an icon into the Workbench
     window. Double-clicking this icon will cause `term' to wake up and
     to return the state is was in before iconification took place.

         @{b}While `term' is iconified, most incoming ARexx-commands will
     be queued and the corresponding ARexx programs will appear to
     `hang'. In order to reactivate the program either double-click on
     the program icon or send the ARexx command @{b}ACTIVATE@{ub}. As soon as
     `term' is `awake' again pending commands will be processed again@{ub}

@{b}About@{ub}
     Shows some information on the program.

@{b}Quit@{ub}
     Terminates the program, hold down a @{b}Shift@{ub} key to quit immediately,
     otherwise you will be prompted to confirm your decision.

   After selecting the `Quit' menu item the program may take a few
seconds to exit since the contents of the @{"Text buffer" Link "Text_buffer"} are freed first.


@EndNode

@Node "Edit" "term.guide/Edit"
@Next "Commands"
@Prev "Project"
@Toc "Menus"

@{u}Edit@{uu}

@{b}Copy@{ub}
     In order to transfer any currently marked screen text to the
     clipboard buffer, select this menu item. Text can be marked by
     double-clicking the select button while the mouse is over a word
     or by clicking the select button and dragging the mouse.

@{b}Paste@{ub}
     Pastes the contents of the clipboard at the current cursor position
     provided that the clipboard contains text data. Hold down either
     @{b}Shift@{ub} key to have `term' include the @{b}Paste prefix@{ub} and the
     @{b}Paste suffix@{ub} (see @{"Clipboard panel" Link "Clipboard_panel"}) along with the clipboard
     contents.

@{b}Clear@{ub}
     Any currently marked text will be released as soon as any rendering
     operations are to be executed in the main window. To release marked
     text manually, select this menu item.


@EndNode

@Node "Commands" "term.guide/Commands"
@Next "Phone"
@Prev "Edit"
@Toc "Menus"

@{u}Commands@{uu}

@{b}Execute AmigaDOS command@{ub}
     Enter the command you want to execute and its command line
     arguments here.

@{b}Execute ARexx command@{ub}
     This function calls the ARexx server to execute a script file. If
     the first input character is a ` or " the input will be considered
     as a small program in a single line. Note that this function will
     not be available if the ARexx server isn't running.

     The ARexx command set supported by `term' is described in the
     `term' ARexx interface documentation.


@EndNode

@Node "Phone" "term.guide/Phone"
@Next "Transfer"
@Prev "Commands"
@Toc "Menus"

@{u}Phone@{uu}

@{b}Phonebook@{ub}
     The phonebook is one of the most powerful and complex functions of
     `term' and will be described later in this document (see
     @{"Phonebook" Link "Phonebook"}).

@{b}Redial@{ub}
     Dialing list entries which the dialing routine was unable to
     establish a connection to are once again passed to the dialer.

@{b}Dial@{ub}
     To dial a single phone number select this menu item. The phone
     number entered will be passed to the dialing routine.

@{b}Send break@{ub}
     Sends a `break' signal across the serial line.

@{b}Hang up@{ub}
     Tells the modem to hang up the serial line.

@{b}Wait...@{ub}
     Will cause `term' to emit the character sequence @{b}<Blank
     space><Backspace>@{ub} every second in order to fool the remote into
     believing that terminal input is currently taking place.

@{b}Flush receive buffer@{ub}
     Tells the serial driver to drop its input buffer contents and
     resets the state of the internal serial buffers.

@{b}Release serial device@{ub}
     The serial driver is released for other programs to use it. A
     requester will appear which allows you to reopen the serial driver
     or to quit `term'.

     If the serial driver has been released by the ARexx interface and
     has not been reopened yet, this menu item will do it.

   If you are still online, the `Redial' and `Dial' menu entries will be
disabled. In order to make another call, hang up the line first.


@EndNode

@Node "Transfer" "term.guide/Transfer"
@Next "Buffer"
@Prev "Phone"
@Toc "Menus"

@{u}Transfer@{uu}

@{b}Upload ASCII file(s)@{ub}
     This is a pure ASCII-file upload implemented through
     @{b}xprascii.library@{ub}. It was added to allow poor BBS programs to
     receive text files (especially Paragon doesn't seem to like ZModem
     text file upload).

@{b}Download ASCII file(s)@{ub}
     This is a pure ASCII-file download implemented through
     @{b}xprascii.library@{ub}. Refer to `Upload ASCII file(s)' for
     features/options of this mode.

@{b}Upload text file(s)@{ub}
     Sends a file/files to the remote receiver using the current
     transfer protocol. If possible this command will `ask' the
     transfer protocol to transmit the file(s) in text mode (whatever
     that means) which may include CR/LF substitution and other
     gimmicks. Consult the library documentation to find out if your
     favourite transfer library supports text mode.

@{b}Download text file(s)@{ub}
     Request a file/files using the current transfer protocol. Refer to
     `Upload text file(s)' for features/options of this mode.

@{b}Edit & upload text file@{ub}
     Invokes the currently selected (see @{"Path panel" Link "Path_panel"}) text editor on a
     file to be selected using a file requester.

     `term' will block and wait until the editor has returned.

     After the editor has returned, the user will be asked whether the
     file edited is to be transferred as plain ASCII or via text upload.

@{b}Upload binary file(s)@{ub}
     Send a file/files to the remote receiver using the current transfer
     protocol. True batch upload is supported both through wildcard
     expressions (@{b}#?.txt@{ub} will send all files whose names end with @{b}.txt@{ub})
     or through multiple selection. Refer to the documentation of your
     favourite transfer library to find out if batch file transfer is
     supported.

@{b}Download binary file(s)@{ub}
     Receive a file/files using the current transfer protocol. If the
     protocol does not support batch download you are required to enter
     the name of the file to be received. Files which remain empty
     after the transfer are deleted automatically.

   The transfer routines open an information window in which a number of
transfer parameters are displayed (see @{"Transfer panel" Link "Transfer_panel"}).


@EndNode

@Node "Buffer" "term.guide/Buffer"
@Next "Terminal"
@Prev "Transfer"
@Toc "Menus"

@{u}Buffer@{uu}

@{b}Clear buffer@{ub}
     Clears the contents of the @{"Text buffer" Link "Text_buffer"}. Any text will be discarded
     and @{b}cannot@{ub} be recovered. Capture files are not affected by this
     command.

@{b}Display buffer@{ub}
     Opens the @{"Text buffer" Link "Text_buffer"} screen.

@{b}Close buffer@{ub}
     Closes the @{"Text buffer" Link "Text_buffer"} screen but does not free the contents.

@{b}Freeze buffer@{ub}
     This menu entry will, if enabled, stop the @{"Text buffer" Link "Text_buffer"} from
     filling up with new text.

@{b}Open buffer...@{ub}
     Loads the contents of the @{"Text buffer" Link "Text_buffer"} from a file. If there are
     still text lines in the @{"Text buffer" Link "Text_buffer"} a requester will appear giving
     you the choice to discard the old data, append the new data, or to
     cancel the action.

@{b}Save buffer as...@{ub}
     Saves the contents of the @{"Text buffer" Link "Text_buffer"} to a file. You will be
     notified if the file to save to exists already (you may discard
     the old file, append the new data or cancel the action).

   More detailed information on the @{"Text buffer" Link "Text_buffer"} will be given later in
this document.


@EndNode

@Node "Terminal" "term.guide/Terminal"
@Next "Settings"
@Prev "Buffer"
@Toc "Menus"

@{u}Terminal@{uu}

@{b}Clear screen@{ub}
     Clears the whole `term' screen and moves the cursor to the top
     left home position.

@{b}Reset font@{ub}
     Will change the screen font back to the default screen font.

@{b}Reset styles@{ub}
     Resets all character style attributes (bold, blinking, inverse
     video, underlined, etc.) and sets the text colour to the default
     pen.

@{b}Reset terminal@{ub}
     Use this menu item to reset the state of the entire terminal
     emulation.


@EndNode

@Node "Settings" "term.guide/Settings"
@Next "Windows"
@Prev "Terminal"
@Toc "Menus"

@{u}Settings@{uu}

   This is where you adjust the program preferences settings. There is a
difference between local and global settings:  local settings can also
be set by making a connection to a mailbox while global settings are
kept even while local settings are active. They have to be changed
explicitely.

@{b}Serial...@{ub}
     See @{"Serial panel" Link "Serial_panel"}

@{b}Modem...@{ub}
     See @{"Modem panel" Link "Modem_panel"}.

@{b}Screen...@{ub}
     See @{"Screen panel" Link "Screen_panel"}.

@{b}Terminal...@{ub}
     See @{"Terminal panel" Link "Terminal_panel"}.

@{b}Emulation...@{ub}
     See @{"Emulation panel" Link "Emulation_panel"}.

@{b}Clipboard...@{ub}
     See @{"Clipboard panel" Link "Clipboard_panel"}.

@{b}Capture...@{ub}
     See @{"Capture panel" Link "Capture_panel"}.

@{b}Commands...@{ub}
     See @{"Command panel" Link "Command_panel"}.

@{b}Miscellaneous...@{ub}
     See @{"Miscellaneous panel" Link "Miscellaneous_panel"}.

@{b}Paths...@{ub}
     See @{"Path panel" Link "Path_panel"}.

@{b}Transfer protocol...@{ub}
     This command allows you to specify the transfer protocol library
     to be employed for up-/downloads.

@{b}Transfer...@{ub}
     The transfer options can be changed with this command. If possible
     a control panel will pop up which allows you to change the current
     parameters by mouse/keyboard. If the selected transfer protocol
     does not provide these option hooks, a simple string requester
     will prompt for input. Consult the documentation of your favourite
     transfer protocol for legal options and the values to which they
     can be set.

@{b}Translation tables...@{ub}
     See @{"Translation panel" Link "Translation_panel"}.

@{b}Function keys...@{ub}
     See @{"Function key panel" Link "Function_key_panel"}.

@{b}Fast! macros...@{ub}
     See @{"Fast macro panel" Link "Fast_macro_panel"}.

@{b}Hotkeys...@{ub}
     See @{"Hotkey panel" Link "Hotkey_panel"}.

@{b}Speech...@{ub}
     See @{"Speech panel" Link "Speech_panel"}.

@{b}Console window...@{ub}
     Whenever an AmigaDOS/ARexx command is executed an output window is
     opened. This menu item will bring up a requester allowing you to
     edit the size and position of the window to be opened (consult
     your AmigaDOS manual for a description of the window position
     string). If you do not want the window to appear, simply enter
     @{b}NIL:@{ub}.


@EndNode

@Node "Windows" "term.guide/Windows"
@Prev "Settings"
@Toc "Menus"

@{u}Windows@{uu}

@{b}Status@{ub}
     This function opens a window to display program status information.
     Click the window to update the information:

    @{b}Session start@{ub}
          When was the program started?

    @{b}Bytes received@{ub}
          The number of bytes received.

    @{b}Bytes sent@{ub}
          The number of bytes sent.

    @{b}Connection message@{ub}
          The string returned by the modem when a connection was made.

    @{b}BBS name@{ub}
          If available, the name of the BBS the modem is currently
          connected to.

    @{b}BBS phone number@{ub}
          If available, the phone number of the BBS the modem is
          currently connected to.

    @{b}BBS comment@{ub}
          If available, the phone book comment corresponding to the BBS
          the modem is currently connected to.

    @{b}BBS user name@{ub}
          If available, the user name, as available through the phone
          book, corresponding to the BBS the modem is currently
          connected to.

    @{b}Screen size@{ub}
          The size of the terminal output window in characters (columns
          / rows).

    @{b}ARexx port name@{ub}
          If available, the name of the ARexx host `term' is currently
          using.

    @{b}Buffer size (bytes)@{ub}
          The size of the @{"Text buffer" Link "Text_buffer"}.

    @{b}Free memory (bytes)@{ub}
          The amount of free system memory.

@{b}Review@{ub}
     A review window is opened which basically displays the same text
     as the text buffer screen. You can scroll through the text
     displayed both by mouse (see the right hand side scroller) and by
     cursor keys.

@{b}Packet@{ub}
     Opens an input window in which a single line of characters to be
     transferred across the serial line can be entered. More on this
     feature is explained under @{"Packet window" Link "Packet_window"} below.

@{b}Fast! macros@{ub}
     Opens or closes the so-called @{"Fast macro panel" Link "Fast_macro_panel"}. The role of the
     @{"Fast! macros" Link "Fast!_macros"} will be discussed later in this text.


@EndNode

@Node "Control_panels" "term.guide/Control panels"
@Next "Text buffer"
@Prev "Menus"
@Toc "Main"

@{u}@{b}Control panels@{uu}@{ub}

   This where all the control panels employed by `term' are explained:


 @{" Serial panel " Link "Serial_panel"}         Serial settings
 @{" Modem panel " Link "Modem_panel"}          Modem settings
 @{" Screen panel " Link "Screen_panel"}         Screen settings
 @{" Terminal panel " Link "Terminal_panel"}       Terminal settings
 @{" Emulation panel " Link "Emulation_panel"}      Terminal emulation control
 @{" Clipboard panel " Link "Clipboard_panel"}      Clipboard settings
 @{" Capture panel " Link "Capture_panel"}        Capture file, log file and text
                        buffer settings
 @{" Command panel " Link "Command_panel"}        Command settings
 @{" Miscellaneous panel " Link "Miscellaneous_panel"}  Miscellaneous settings
 @{" Path panel " Link "Path_panel"}           Path settings
 @{" Function key panel " Link "Function_key_panel"}   Function key settings
 @{" Cursor key panel " Link "Cursor_key_panel"}     Cursor key settings
 @{" Fast macro panel " Link "Fast_macro_panel"}     Fast macro settings
 @{" Hotkey panel " Link "Hotkey_panel"}         Hotkey settings
 @{" Speech panel " Link "Speech_panel"}         Speech settings
 @{" Transfer panel " Link "Transfer_panel"}       Data transfer control
 @{" Translation panel " Link "Translation_panel"}    Character translation control
 @{" Phonebook " Link "Phonebook"}            The phone directory
 @{" Rate panel " Link "Rate_panel"}           Phone rate control
 @{" Copy panel " Link "Copy_panel"}           Copying of configuration elements
 @{" Dial panel " Link "Dial_panel"}           Dialing control
 @{" Printing panel " Link "Printing_panel"}       Phonebook printing control


@EndNode

@Node "Serial_panel" "term.guide/Serial panel"
@Next "Modem panel"
@Prev "Control panels"
@Toc "Control panels"

@{u}Serial panel@{uu}

   This is where the serial parameters may be changed.

@{b}Baud rate@{ub}
     Transfer speed in bits per second.

@{b}Bits/char@{ub}
     Number of bits per transferred character (7 or 8).

@{b}Parity@{ub}
     Serial parity (none, odd, even, mark or space).

@{b}Stop bits@{ub}
     Number of stop bits (1 or 2).

@{b}Handshaking@{ub}
     Serial handshaking mode (RTS/CTS, RTS/CTS with DRS signal check,
     none).

@{b}Duplex@{ub}
     Determines whether characters are echoed back to the terminal
     screen or not (full, half = local echo).

@{b}Buffer size@{ub}
     The number to be specified here allows to set the serial driver I/O
     buffer size. @{b}Every number you enter here will result in `term' and
     the serial driver allocating twice the buffer size (this is only a
     word of warning for those among us who prefer buffer sizes of 256K
     and up).@{ub}

@{b}Break length@{ub}
     Length of the break signal given in microseconds.

@{b}Strip bit 8@{ub}
     For those guys and gals who need it:  if this switch is effect each
     character received or transmitted by `term' will have its
     high-order bit cleared.

@{b}High-speed mode@{ub}
     Activates a special mode of the serial driver which is to skip a
     couple of internal parity and stop bits checks resulting in higher
     data throughput rate. @{b}If this switch is turned on, the serial
     parameters will be reset to 8 bits per char, no parity and 1 stop
     bit.@{ub}

@{b}Check carrier@{ub}
     `term' will recognize the @{b}NO CARRIER@{ub} message a modem emits when
     the carrier line signal drops back to low. For maximum safety,
     `term' will also check the carrier signal line after receiving the
     @{b}NO CARRIER@{ub} message if this switch is enabled. This is to make
     sure that no accidentally appearing string causes confusion.

     If this switch is enabled, `term' will check the carrier signal
     during file transfers and will abort the transfer if the signal is
     lost.

         @{b}Note:  Be sure to switch this feature off in case you wish to
     transfer files using a null-modem cable!@{ub}

@{b}Shared access@{ub}
     Requested by many (two to be accurate) users, this switch allows
     you to run the serial driver in shared access mode. Not all driver
     types will allow this to happen.

@{b}xON/xOFF@{ub}
     This switch enables the processing of the flow-control characters
     @{b}xON@{ub} (= @{b}Control + S@{ub}) and @{b}xOFF@{ub} (= @{b}Control + Q@{ub}).

@{b}Pass ^S/^Q through@{ub}
     If this switch is enabled, `term' will pass the @{b}xON@{ub}/@{b}xOFF@{ub}
     characters through to the modem rather than swallowing them.

@{b}Serial device@{ub}
     The name of the serial driver to be used by `term'. This is usually
     @{b}serial.device@{ub} (@{b}modem?.device@{ub} for the internal Supra modem,
     @{b}sxbios.device@{ub} for ASDG's serial IO card).

@{b}Device unit number@{ub}
     The device unit number of the serial driver selected above. This is
     usually left `0' but can also be used to address multiple serial IO
     ports.

@{b}Use@{ub}
     Accept the current settings.

@{b}Default (phone book only)@{ub}
     Drop the current settings, making a connection to the corresponding
     phone number will leave the corresponding main configuration entry
     unchanged.

@{b}Cancel@{ub}
     Don't use the current settings.

   Most modems will not recognize a sudden change in the baud rate. Type
@{b}AT<RETURN>@{ub} to make the change known.

   If `RTS/CTS (DSR)' handshaking is selected, `term' will check to see
if the @{b}Data set ready@{ub} line happens to be high active. If not, it will
default back to software handshaking (@{b}xON@{ub}/@{b}xOFF@{ub}). The @{b}RTS/CTS@{ub}
handshaking mode will ignore the presence or absence of the @{b}DSR@{ub} signal.

   `term' will take advantage of Christopher Whichura's
@{b}OwnDevUnit.library@{ub} if installed in your system, allowing controlled
access to the serial driver's resources.


@EndNode

@Node "Modem_panel" "term.guide/Modem panel"
@Next "Screen panel"
@Prev "Serial panel"
@Toc "Control panels"

@{u}Modem panel@{uu}

   This is where modem control strings and other related parameters are
configured.

@{b}Modem init command@{ub}
     The string to send to the modem after successful program
     initialization. This string is optional and does not need to be
     entered.

     The dialing routine will use the initialization string entered here
     before dialing a phone number.

@{b}Modem exit command@{ub}
     The string to be sent to the modem shortly before the program
     terminates. Just like the modem init string this string is
     optional and does not need to be entered.

     The dialing routine will use the initialization string entered here
     before dialing the next telephone number.

@{b}Hangup command@{ub}
     The string to be sent to the modem when asked to hang up the line.
     This string does have to be present if the @{b}Drop DTR on hangup@{ub}
     switch is enabled.

@{b}Dial prefix@{ub}
     The string to be used to prefix each dialing command. This is
     usually a variant of @{b}ATDP@{ub} or @{b}ATDT@{ub}.

@{b}Dial suffix@{ub}
     The string to be used to append to each dialing command. This is
     usually the carriage-return character @{b}\r@{ub}.

@{b}`No carrier' message@{ub}
     The message the modem emits if the data carrier is lost. The
     program uses this to determine the length of the connection and to
     calculate the how much the user is to pay for it.

@{b}`Connect' message@{ub}
     The message the modem emits after detecting a carrier signal.
     `term' uses this input to determine successful telephone
     connection, to reconfigure itself and to start the online timer.

@{b}`No dialtone' message@{ub}
     The message to be returned by the modem in case it does not
     encounter any dialing tone on the phone line.

@{b}`Voice' message@{ub}
     The message `term' is expected to receive if the modem detects a
     voice call. If in dialing mode, `term' will abort the process. The
     user will in any case be notified of the event.

@{b}`Ring' message@{ub}
     The message the modem emits if it receives a call, same effects as
     with the `Voice message'.

@{b}`Busy' message@{ub}
     The message the modem returns if the number which has just been
     dialed is busy.

@{b}Redial delay@{ub}
     The time to wait after walking through the whole dialing list
     without making any successful connection before another attempt is
     started.

@{b}Number of dial retries@{ub}
     The number of times the dialer walks through the dialing list
     trying to make a successful connection before giving up.

@{b}Dial timeout@{ub}
     The time to wait for a successful connection during dialing. After
     this time has elapsed, the dialer will skip to the next entry in
     the list.

@{b}Redial after hanging up@{ub}
     If this switch is in effect, `term' will redial all the phone
     numbers still in the dialing list as soon as the line is hung up
     or the carrier signal is lost.

@{b}Connect auto-baud@{ub}
     Most modems echo the baud rate upon successful connection. If
     enabled the baud rate will be read and set for the serial driver.

@{b}Drop DTR on hangup@{ub}
     Some modems will track the @{b}data terminal ready@{ub} line in order to
     make sure that the terminal program is listening, once the line
     goes back to low potential, these modems will drop the line and
     hang up. Use this button to enable this feature.

@{b}Use@{ub}
     Use the current settings.

@{b}Default (phone book only)@{ub}
     Drop the current settings, making a connection to the corresponding
     phone number will leave the corresponding main configuration entry
     unchanged.

@{b}Cancel@{ub}
     Keep original settings.


@EndNode

@Node "Screen_panel" "term.guide/Screen panel"
@Next "Terminal panel"
@Prev "Modem panel"
@Toc "Control panels"

@{u}Screen panel@{uu}

@{b}Display modes@{ub}
     All display modes available for the main screen are displayed here.

         @{b}The A2024-modes should only be used in connection with an
     A2024/Hedley-monitor. Otherwise the screen may `crash' and working
     with `term' will not be possible any longer.@{ub}

@{b}Colour@{ub}
     This button determines the colour-mode the terminal emulation is
     going to use. Until now, three modes have been implemented:

    @{b}4 Colours (Amiga)@{ub}
          Four colours, optionally blinking.

    @{b}8 Colours (ANSI)@{ub}
          Eight colours, optionally blinking.

    @{b}16 Colours (EGA)@{ub}
          Sixteen colours, as the EGA-palette.

    @{b}2 Colours (Monochrome)@{ub}
          Monochrome, two colours.

@{b}Palette@{ub}
     These buttons are used to select a colour of the screen palette
     that is to be changed.

@{b}Red/Green/Blue@{ub}
     Use these sliders to modify the red, green and blue components of
     the currently active colour.

@{b}Use default colours@{ub}
     Press this button to have the current colour palette set to the
     built-in default colours.

@{b}Screen font@{ub}
     The name of the current user-interface font is displayed here.

@{b}Select new screen font@{ub}
     Press this button to select a new font to be used for the
     user-interface design.

@{b}Make screen public@{ub}
     As dealt with before, the `term' mainscreen is opened as `public'.
     With this button the user may define if other applications are
     allowed to open up their windows on the `term' screen.

@{b}`Shanghai' windows@{ub}
     This item, which is only displayed if `Make screen public' has been
     selected, is closely related to the function before. If active, all
     windows that will normally be displayed on the Workbench screen
     will open on the `term' main screen.

@{b}Blinking@{ub}
     If selected the VT100-blink option is enabled. If running in eight
     colour mode, `term' will only use three bitplanes instead of four
     for text display.

@{b}Faster layout@{ub}
     Activating this switch will slow down display updates and window
     management. Oh well, not always, there may be a speed increase with
     some configurations, such as with external emulations activated or
     when using more than four colours on the screen.

     I suggest to experiment with the effects of this button before
     actually using it.

@{b}Screen title@{ub}
     If this button is enabled, the `term' screen will contain a
     draggable title bar, if not, the title bar will be disabled,
     leaving more space for the terminal output window.

@{b}Use public screen@{ub}
     `term' does not necessarily open a custom screen, this switch will
     make the main and auxilary windows appear on a named public
     screen. `term' will try to adapt colours and text rendering modes
     to its new environment. It will share the screen palette with
     other applications which makes it possible to run the built-in
     terminal emulation in eight or sixteen colours provided that
     enough shareable screen pens are available (note:  Kickstart 3.0
     required). `term' will inherit the text font to be used for
     user-interface layout from the public screen it will open its
     window on. As of Kickstart 2.04 `term' will fall back to opening a
     custom screen in case the public screen text font happens to be
     proportional-spaced.

         @{b}Note:  only the built-in terminal emulation is guaranteed to
     take advantage of pen-sharing facilities, external emulation
     libraries will most likely fail to display text correctly!@{ub}

     Take care when resizing the `term' main window as a size change
     will reset the terminal emulation.

@{b}Public screen name@{ub}
     The name of the public screen `term' is to open windows on. `term'
     will fall back to the Workbench screen if no proper name is given
     (i.e. no name is entered) or the desired screen is unavailable.

@{b}Status line@{ub}
     This switch allows to disable the status line display or to change
     between two alternative status line displays:

    @{b}Disabled@{ub}
          No status line is displayed.

    @{b}Standard@{ub}
          The standard two status lines are displayed.

    @{b}Compact@{ub}
          A very condensed version of the status line is displayed,
          only the data is shown but no captions. The data is displayed
          in the following order:

            1. Status

            2. Terminal type

            3. Transfer protocol

            4. Baud rate

            5. Serial parameters

            6. Time of day

            7. Online time

@{b}Use@{ub}
     Use the current settings.

@{b}Default (phone book only)@{ub}
     Drop the current settings, making a connection to the corresponding
     phone number will leave the corresponding main configuration entry
     unchanged.

@{b}Cancel@{ub}
     Keep the old settings.

   Some display modes (such as Super-Hires, Productivity, etc.) restrict
the number of screen colours on ECS machines. Instead of 16 bit
portions for red, green and blue only 2-bit portions are used which
leads to a maximum width of the palette of at all 64 colours. This is
not a `feature' of `term', but a hardware restriction.


@EndNode

@Node "Terminal_panel" "term.guide/Terminal panel"
@Next "Emulation panel"
@Prev "Screen panel"
@Toc "Control panels"

@{u}Terminal panel@{uu}

   All settings that may be done here determine the behaviour of the
terminal itself, i.e. how command sequences are interpreted and
displayed.

@{b}Bell@{ub}
     This is where you select the action(s) `term' is to take whenever a
     `bell' character turns up in the data stream:

    @{b}Visual@{ub}
          The screen will flash.

    @{b}Audible@{ub}
          An audible signal will be generated.

    @{b}Visual & audible@{ub}
          A combination of both effects.

    @{b}Ignore@{ub}
          Nothing will happen.

    @{b}System default@{ub}
          The system beep routines will be used.

@{b}Alert@{ub}
     `term' notifies the user of certain events, such as a connection
     being established or a file transfer action which has just been
     finished. This switch allows you to select the type of
     notification:

    @{b}Bell@{ub}
          A bell signal will be given.

    @{b}Screen@{ub}
          The `term' screen will be brought to the front.

    @{b}Bell/Screen@{ub}
          A combination of the two actions above.

    @{b}None@{ub}
          Nothing will happen.

@{b}Emulation@{ub}
     At this point the user may select the terminal emulation. First
     there is a solid VT102/VT220/ANSI emulation which supports all
     common commandsequences, then there is a so called `Atomic'
     emulation which does only support the very basic command-sequences
     (CR, LF, Backspace, etc.), all VT102- and ANSI-command-sequences
     are suppressed, and, last but not least, a `TTY'-emulation which
     does not suppress all command-sequences, as `Atomic' does, but
     rather echoes them to the screen.

     In addition to the built-in terminal emulation, `term' also
     supports external terminal emulations. To select one, set the
     terminal emulation type to `External' and enter the name of the
     emulation in the string gadget below (the file may alternatively
     selected by hitting the `Select new emulation' button). In case
     anything goes wrong loading or initializing the terminal emulation
     library, `term' will switch back to the built-in `ANSI/VT'
     emulation.

@{b}Emulation name@{ub}
     The name of an external terminal emulation library to be used by
     `term' instead of the built-in emulation code.

@{b}Font@{ub}
     Here the type of the font to be used for text display in the
     terminal window can be selected:

    @{b}Standard@{ub}
          The standard text font.

    @{b}IBM-PC style@{ub}
          A font similar to the IBM-PC text font will be used. @{b}This
          requires the @{b}IBM.font@{ub} to be present in the @{b}Fonts:@{ub} directory.@{ub}
          No matter how the translation tables (see @{"Translation panel" Link "Translation_panel"})
          are configured, outgoing Amiga characters are translated into
          PC character values.

    @{b}IBM-PC style (raw)@{ub}
          This selection has very much the same effect as @{b}IBM-PC style@{ub}
          but no character translation is involved.

@{b}Text font@{ub}
     Here the name of the standard terminal window text font is
     displayed.

@{b}Select new text font@{ub}
     Press this button to select a new terminal window text font.

@{b}Send CR@{ub}
     This button determines the sequence that is sent to the remote if a
     carriage-return is issued.

    @{b}As CR@{ub}
          Without any change

    @{b}As CR+LF@{ub}
          Carriage-return and linefeed

    @{b}Ignore@{ub}
          Suppress any carriage-return

@{b}Send LF@{ub}
     This button determines the sequence that is sent to the remote if a
     linefeed is issued.

    @{b}As LF@{ub}
          Without any change

    @{b}As LF+CR@{ub}
          Linefeed and carriage-return

    @{b}Ignore@{ub}
          Suppress any linefeed

@{b}Receive CR@{ub}
@{b}Receive LF@{ub}
     These two buttons have largely the same effect as the @{b}Send CR/LF@{ub}
     buttons, they are different in that they affect the incoming data
     rather than the data transmitted.

@{b}Columns@{ub}
     The number of columns to use for the terminal window. The minimum
     value is 20 columns, the maximum value is defined by the actual
     screen size.

@{b}Lines@{ub}
     The number of lines to use for the terminal window. The minimum
     value is 20 lines, the maximum value is defined by the actual
     screen size.

@{b}Keymap file@{ub}
     If your installation requires that `term' is to use a custom keymap
     layout, enter the keymap file name here.

         @{b}At the time of this writing the program will not support custom
     keymap layouts with the @{"Packet window" Link "Packet_window"} due to operating system
     limitations.@{ub}

@{b}Bell sound file@{ub}
     The name of the IFF-8SVX sound file that will be played if a @{b}BEL@{ub}
     signal is detected. This file may for technical reasons not be
     larger than 102,400 bytes.

@{b}Use@{ub}
     Use the current settings.

@{b}Default (phone book only)@{ub}
     Drop the current settings, making a connection to the corresponding
     phone number will leave the corresponding main configuration entry
     unchanged.

@{b}Cancel@{ub}
     Keep the old settings.


@EndNode

@Node "Emulation_panel" "term.guide/Emulation panel"
@Next "Clipboard panel"
@Prev "Terminal panel"
@Toc "Control panels"

@{u}Emulation panel@{uu}

   The buttons found here allow you to change the internal parameters of
the selected emulation.

   The following text only describes the parameters to change when using
the built-in terminal emulation; if an external terminal emulation is in
effect, this menu will conjure up the corresponding parameters menu
supported by the external terminal emulation module.

@{b}Cursor keys@{ub}
     If this mode is active the cursor keys transmit a command-sequence
     instead of a cursor move event. If the remote computer needs these
     sequences, this mode -- applications mode -- can be activated with
     this button.

@{b}Numeric keypad@{ub}
     If this mode is activated the keys of the numeric keypad transmit a
     command-sequence instead of a number. If the remote computer needs
     these sequences, this mode -- applications mode -- can be
     activated with this button.

@{b}Wrap cursor moves@{ub}
     According to the VT100-specification the cursor movements have to
     stop at the edges of the screen. In spite of this the cursor may
     leave these borders, especially in ANSI-mode, and may appear at
     the other side of the screen. This button activates a more
     `tolerant' mode.

@{b}Wrap characters@{ub}
     This function activates the automatical carriage return function
     which is triggered as soon as the cursor crosses the right screen
     margin. To avoid unpleasant side-effects, this gadget should be
     activated all the time.

@{b}Insert mode@{ub}
     Normally, `term' is in overwrite-mode (characters entered
     overwrite the contents of the screen). If this gadget is
     activated, typed characters are inserted by pushing all the
     characters right of the cursor towards the right margin.

         @{b}The insert-mode does only work for lines. If characters are
     pushed out of the screen they cannot be restored.@{ub}

@{b}New-line mode@{ub}
     This gadget activates a special mode in which some
     VT100-control-sequences cause `term' to perform a linefeed instead
     of clearing the screen or other serious changes of the contents of
     the screen.

@{b}Font scale@{ub}
     VT-100 offers several different sizes of fonts. Some can be
     selected with this gadget:

    @{b}Normal@{ub}
          The normal height of the font.

    @{b}Half width@{ub}
          Half width of font.

@{b}Scrolling@{ub}
     This button selects one of two different scrolling modes:  smooth
     or jumping.

@{b}Destructive backspace@{ub}
     Determines if the @{b}Backspace@{ub} code, which will delete the character
     left from the cursor, only moves the cursor to the left or removes
     the character from the screen.

@{b}Swap `Backspace' and `Del' keys@{ub}
     For the die-hard VT100 user:  if this switch is enabled the roles
     of the backspace key and the delete key are reversed. @{b}This also
     applies to sequences such as @{b}Control + H@{ub} which will produce a
     delete character instead of a backspace character.@{ub}

@{b}Printer control enabled@{ub}
     `term' supports the standard VT220 printer control commands. If you
     don't want the application on the other side of the line to play
     with the printer the printer support commands can be disabled with
     this switch. If disabled `term' will act like a VT220 terminal
     with no printer attached.

@{b}Answerback message@{ub}
     The string to send across the serial line whenever an @{b}ENQ@{ub}
     character is received. The string is -- as usual -- a command
     sequence.

@{b}Use@{ub}
     Use the current settings.

@{b}Default (phone book only)@{ub}
     Drop the current settings, making a connection to the corresponding
     phone number will leave the corresponding main configuration entry
     unchanged.

@{b}Cancel@{ub}
     Keep the old settings.


@EndNode

@Node "Clipboard_panel" "term.guide/Clipboard panel"
@Next "Capture panel"
@Prev "Emulation panel"
@Toc "Control panels"

@{u}Clipboard panel@{uu}

@{b}Clipboard unit@{ub}
     The clipboard supports several units (0-255) which can be accessed
     independently. It can make sense to change this value but
     generally you will probably leave it as unit `0'.

@{b}Clipboard character delay@{ub}
     When pasting the clipboard contents this number determines how many
     seconds to wait before sending the next character.

@{b}Clipboard line delay@{ub}
     When pasting the clipboard contents this number determines how many
     seconds to wait before sending the line-termination character
     (carriage return).

@{b}Paste prefix@{ub}
     If enabled, the text to send before the clipboard contents are fed
     into the input stream, see @{"Clipboard" Link "Clipboard"}.

@{b}Paste suffix@{ub}
     If enabled, the text to send after the clipboard contents are fed
     into the input stream, see @{"Clipboard" Link "Clipboard"}.

@{b}Use@{ub}
     Use the current settings.

@{b}Default (phone book only)@{ub}
     Drop the current settings, making a connection to the corresponding
     phone number will leave the corresponding main configuration entry
     unchanged.

@{b}Cancel@{ub}
     Keep the old settings.


@EndNode

@Node "Capture_panel" "term.guide/Capture panel"
@Next "Command panel"
@Prev "Clipboard panel"
@Toc "Control panels"

@{u}Capture panel@{uu}

@{b}Log actions@{ub}
     If enabled will write a protocol of each program action (uploads,
     downloads, dial attempts, etc.) to a file. Each action is listed
     along with time and date. Carrier-lost events will also note the
     approximate cost of the call.

@{b}Log file@{ub}
     The name of the file in which the information on the actions
     executed by `term' will be logged if @{b}Log actions@{ub} is enabled.

@{b}Log calls@{ub}
     If this switch is enabled, `term' will create call-log files in a
     format compatible with the @{b}NComm@{ub} terminal program.

@{b}Call log file@{ub}
     The name of the file in which the information on calls made by
     `term' will be logged if @{b}Log calls@{ub} is enabled.

@{b}Maximum text buffer size@{ub}
     To save memory, a high-water mark concerning the maximum amount of
     memory the @{"Text buffer" Link "Text_buffer"} will allocate for text may be specified.
     The minimum value to be entered here is 2,000 bytes which are
     roughly equivalent to two @{"Text buffer" Link "Text_buffer"} pages of text. A value of 0
     will cause the @{"Text buffer" Link "Text_buffer"} to always allocate as much memory as
     required to buffer all the incoming text.

@{b}Text buffer enabled@{ub}
     This switch works in conjunction with the `Freeze buffer' menu
     entry (freezing the @{"Text buffer" Link "Text_buffer"} contents). In fact, the menu entry
     is adjusted according to the configuration settings whenever a new
     configuration is invoked (that is, whenever a new connection is
     made through the dialing panel or at program startup time). @{b}`term'
     will only freeze the buffer if this switch is set, it will leave
     the buffer state (frozen or not) untouched if this switch is not
     enabled.@{ub}

@{b}Text buffer file path@{ub}
     The path the file requester will bring up when saving the contents
     of the text buffer.

@{b}Connect-auto-capture@{ub}
     If enabled will automatically open a capture file after
     successfully making a connection. Any other already open capture
     file will be closed before proceeding.

@{b}Capture filter enabled@{ub}
     If selected, command sequences are filtered out before the incoming
     characters are captured to disk or printer.

@{b}Capture file path@{ub}
     This string gadget contain the path in which the the capture files
     will be created if @{b}Connect-auto-capture@{ub} is enabled.

@{b}Use@{ub}
     Use the current settings.

@{b}Default (phone book only)@{ub}
     Drop the current settings, making a connection to the corresponding
     phone number will leave the corresponding main configuration entry
     unchanged.

@{b}Cancel@{ub}
     Keep the old settings.


@EndNode

@Node "Command_panel" "term.guide/Command panel"
@Next "Miscellaneous panel"
@Prev "Capture panel"
@Toc "Control panels"

@{u}Command panel@{uu}

   Here you will find entries for four command sequences which serve
four functions:

@{b}Startup/Login macro@{ub}
     At the beginning of every session with `term' and after a
     connection has been established by the dialing routine a
     command-sequence is executed which may execute command-files or
     perform a automatical `login'.

@{b}Logoff macro@{ub}
     The macro to execute when the line is hung up or the carrier
     signal is lost.

@{b}Upload macro@{ub}
     `term' will execute this macro after a successful upload has been
     made.

@{b}Download macro@{ub}
     `term' will execute this macro after a successful download has
     been made.

@{b}Use@{ub}
     Use the current settings.

@{b}Default (phone book only)@{ub}
     Drop the current settings, making a connection to the corresponding
     phone number will leave the corresponding main configuration entry
     unchanged.

@{b}Cancel@{ub}
     Keep the old settings.


@EndNode

@Node "Miscellaneous_panel" "term.guide/Miscellaneous panel"
@Next "Path panel"
@Prev "Command panel"
@Toc "Control panels"

@{u}Miscellaneous panel@{uu}

   This is the place where options can be set which would not fit into
other control panels

@{b}Program priority@{ub}
     Use this slider to determine the priority under which the `term'
     main process is to operate. Adjusting this value can make `term'
     perform more reliably in a system which experiences heavy task
     loading. It is recommended to play with this value until a
     satisfactory state is found, setting the program priority too high
     or too low may affect the performance of coprocess-services such
     as the double-buffered file I/O routines.

@{b}Backup configuration@{ub}
     By default the local program configuration saved along with a
     phonebook entry will replace the global configuration as soon as a
     successful connection is made. If this switch is enabled, `term'
     will remember the global configuration in effect before the
     configuration data of a phonebook entry is adopted. As soon as the
     serial driver loses track of the carrier signal or the user
     chooses to hang up the line, `term' will switch back to the
     previous global configuration.

@{b}Show fast! macros@{ub}
     If this switch is enabled, the @{"Fast macro panel" Link "Fast_macro_panel"} will be opened
     whenever the current configuration becomes active (e.g. at startup
     time).

@{b}Release serial device when iconified@{ub}
     By default the serial device driver is released when `term' is
     iconified. Unfortunately, some modems drop the line when the
     device is closed so this switch allows you to keep the link.

@{b}Override transfer path@{ub}
     Each batch file transfer protocol allows you to specify the name
     of the directory to place the files it receives in. By default
     `term' will redirect the files to a directory to be specified in
     the @{"Path panel" Link "Path_panel"}. If this switch is disabled, the internal settings
     of the current transfer protocol will be used.

@{b}Use auto upload panel@{ub}
     Some users found the so-called `ZModem auto-upload panel' to be
     invoked whenever `term' encounters the ZModem inquiry sequence
     rather disturbing, this switch will allow them to disable this
     feature.

@{b}Set `archived' bit@{ub}
     If enabled, this switch will cause `term' to set the @{b}Archived@{ub} bit
     on files transferred using the XPR-interface.

@{b}Transfer file icons@{ub}
     This switch works in conjunction with the drag & upload feature
     (see @{"Transfer panel" Link "Transfer_panel"}). By default, `term' will upload only the files
     whose icons are dragged on the main window, if this switch is in
     effect the icon files will be transferred as well.

@{b}File comment@{ub}
     This is where the action to perform on downloaded files can be set:

    @{b}Ignore@{ub}
          The file comment will not be touched.

    @{b}File type@{ub}
          The file will be examined and a guess will be made which type
          of file it is. The file comment will be set to the name of
          the file type.

    @{b}Source and time@{ub}
          The current BBS name and the time the file was received are
          placed in the file comment.

@{b}Use@{ub}
     Use the current settings.

@{b}Default (phone book only)@{ub}
     Drop the current settings, making a connection to the corresponding
     phone number will leave the corresponding main configuration entry
     unchanged.

@{b}Cancel@{ub}
     Keep the old settings.


@EndNode

@Node "Path_panel" "term.guide/Path panel"
@Next "Translation panel"
@Prev "Miscellaneous panel"
@Toc "Control panels"

@{u}Path panel@{uu}

   In this part of the settings all paths, which `term' uses to save or
load any data, can be determined.

@{b}...Uploadpath@{ub}
@{b}...Downloadpath@{ub}
     The directories in which the functions contained in the `Transfer'
     menu will search and create files.

@{b}Configuration storage directory@{ub}
     The directory that will contain all configuration files (Phonebook,
     Macrokeys, etc.). The default configuration file is called
     @{b}term.prefs@{ub} and will be searched in the path defined by the
     enviroment variable @{b}TERMCONFIGPATH@{ub} (see @{"Environment variables" Link "Environment_variables"}).

@{b}Text editor@{ub}
     Contains the name and search path of the editor used by `Edit &
     upload text file' in the @{"Transfer" Link "Transfer"} menu.

@{b}`term' help text file@{ub}
     This is where the name of the online-help text file is stored. By
     default this is @{b}PROGDIR:term.guide@{ub}.

@{b}Use@{ub}
     Use the current settings.

@{b}Default (phone book only)@{ub}
     Drop the current settings, making a connection to the corresponding
     phone number will leave the corresponding main configuration entry
     unchanged.

@{b}Cancel@{ub}
     Keep the old settings.


@EndNode

@Node "Translation_panel" "term.guide/Translation panel"
@Next "Function key panel"
@Prev "Path panel"
@Toc "Control panels"

@{u}Translation panel@{uu}

   `term' is capable of replacing any incoming and outgoing character
with custom text. This may come in handy with the numerous incarnations
of the dreaded IBM PC font. The control panel to be opened features a
large list of buttons, each single one representing a single character.
Some characters are shown with their corresponding glyphs, some with
their symbolic names and some as plain numbers. Clicking on one of the
buttons will bring up a control panel which allows setting the text to
be received by the terminal emulation when a certain character is
received and the text to be sent when a certain characters is
transmitted.

   Both texts can consist of standard @{"Command sequences" Link "Command_sequences"}, except for the
following commands which are not supported:  @{b}\a@{ub}, @{b}\c@{ub}, @{b}\d@{ub}, @{b}\g@{ub}, @{b}\i@{ub}, @{b}\p@{ub}, @{b}\u@{ub}
and @{b}\x@{ub}.

   Please note that the translation does not come for free, terminal
input and output speed may suffer.

   As of this writing only a few translation table files (see below) are
included in the distribution. If you wish to create translation tables
for IBM doorway mode, national IBM-PC style font variants, etc. feel
free to send them to me. I will try to include them in the next `term'
release.

   Currently included in the `term' distribution are the following
translation table files:

@{b}ISO-4-(GB).prefs@{ub}
     British 7 bit (ISO code 4) character set.

@{b}ISO-10-(S).prefs@{ub}
     Swedish 7 bit (ISO code 10) character set.

@{b}ISO-11-(S).prefs@{ub}
     Swedish 7 bit (ISO code 11) character set.

@{b}ISO-15-(I).prefs@{ub}
     Italian 7 bit (ISO code 15) character set.

@{b}ISO-16-(P).prefs@{ub}
     Portuguese 7 bit (ISO code 16) character set.

@{b}ISO-17-(E).prefs@{ub}
     Spanish 7 bit (ISO code 17) character set.

@{b}ISO-21-(D).prefs@{ub}
     German 7 bit (ISO code 21) character set.

@{b}ISO-60-(N).prefs@{ub}
     Norwegian 7 bit (ISO code 60) character set.

@{b}ISO-61-(N).prefs@{ub}
     Norwegian 7 bit (ISO code 61) character set.

@{b}ISO-69-(F).prefs@{ub}
     French 7 bit (ISO code 69) character set.

@{b}PC-8.prefs@{ub}
     Character translation for standard IBM-PC style font. If you wish
     to use these translation tables, make sure to set the @{b}Font@{ub} type in
     the @{"Terminal panel" Link "Terminal_panel"} to @{b}IBM-PC style (raw)@{ub}.

   Unfortunately, there is no translation available for the Norvegian
and Danish variants of the PC-8 character set as I do not yet have a
fitting Amiga font available. Similar reasons have yet prevented to
implement PC-850 character set support.


@EndNode

@Node "Function_key_panel" "term.guide/Function key panel"
@Next "Cursor key panel"
@Prev "Translation panel"
@Toc "Control panels"

@{u}Function key panel@{uu}

   This control panel allows setting user definable texts for all ten
function keys. All texts are considered @{"Command sequences" Link "Command_sequences"}, a topic
which will be covered later in this document.

@{b}Modifier@{ub}
     All in all 40 keys may be covered with user defined
     @{"Command sequences" Link "Command_sequences"}. As the Amiga keyboard only has ten
     function-keys this button switches between the modifier keys
     (@{b}Shift@{ub}, @{b}Control@{ub}, @{b}Alt@{ub}) which, if pressed in addition which
     a function key, will execute one of the 40 command sequences.

@{b}Load@{ub}
     Load the function key settings from a file.

@{b}Save@{ub}
     Save the function key settings to a file.

@{b}Use@{ub}
     Use the current settings.

@{b}Cancel@{ub}
     Keep the old settings.

   As the definition of the function keys with command sequences
contradicts the standard definition of the four functions keys of a
VT-100-terminal, the keys @{b}F1@{ub}-@{b}F4@{ub}, which may be executed by pressing the
@{b}Shift@{ub} key and the approriate function-key simultaneously, are
mapped to the standard sequences for function-keys. The user may -- of
course -- change these settings.

   If an external terminal emulation happens to be active, those
function keys the emulation has allocated for itself will be disabled
and cannot be edited.


@EndNode

@Node "Cursor_key_panel" "term.guide/Cursor key panel"
@Next "Fast macro panel"
@Prev "Function key panel"
@Toc "Control panels"

@{u}@{b}Cursor key panel@{uu}@{ub}

   This control panel both works and looks similar to the
@{"Function key panel" Link "Function_key_panel"}, the only difference is that it is to assign command
sequences to the cursor keys rather than to the function keys.
Displayed are the assignments for all four cursor keys and the
following buttons:

@{b}Modifier@{ub}
     Any cursor key can be pressed along with one of the modifier keys
     (@{b}Shift@{ub}, @{b}Control@{ub}, @{b}Alt@{ub}). This button will switch between the
     different assignments.

@{b}Load@{ub}
     Load the cursor key settings from a file.

@{b}Save@{ub}
     Save the cursor key settings to a file.

@{b}Use@{ub}
     Use the current settings.

@{b}Cancel@{ub}
     Keep the old settings.


@EndNode

@Node "Fast_macro_panel" "term.guide/Fast macro panel"
@Next "Hotkey panel"
@Prev "Cursor key panel"
@Toc "Control panels"

@{u}Fast macro panel@{uu}

   The design and implementation of the settings to be configured in
this menu are closely related to the menu entry @{"Function key panel" Link "Function_key_panel"}
discussed before, the only difference to be seen in the fact that the
fast! macros are mapped to buttons rather than function keys (more on
this topic later in this document, see @{"Fast! macros" Link "Fast!_macros"}).

@{b}Macro list@{ub}
     The list of macros entered yet, to edit one of these, select it by
     clicking the mouse button with the mouse pointer on it.

@{b}Macro@{ub}
     The name of a macro by which it is listed in the fast! macro list.

@{b}Macro code@{ub}
     The command sequence (see @{"Command sequences" Link "Command_sequences"}) associated with a
     fast! macro. Command sequences are discussed later in this
     document.

@{b}New@{ub}
     Appends a new macro to the list. The user may then select and
     customize it.

@{b}Delete@{ub}
     Removes the currently selected macro from the list.

@{b}Load@{ub}
     Loads the macro list from a file.

@{b}Save@{ub}
     Saves the macro list to a file.

@{b}Top@{ub}
     Places the currently selected macro at the top of the list.

@{b}Up@{ub}
     Moves the currently selected macro one entry up.

@{b}Down@{ub}
     Moves the currently selected macro one entry down.

@{b}End@{ub}
     Places the currently selected macro at the end of the list.


@EndNode

@Node "Hotkey_panel" "term.guide/Hotkey panel"
@Next "Speech panel"
@Prev "Fast macro panel"
@Toc "Control panels"

@{u}Hotkey panel@{uu}

   This is where the key sequences used to arrange screens and to
execute special functions are to be configured.

@{b}term screen to front@{ub}
     The keys to press to bring the `term' screen to the front.

@{b}Buffer screen to front@{ub}
     The keys to press to bring the screen of the @{"Text buffer" Link "Text_buffer"} process
     to the front.

@{b}Skip dial entry@{ub}
     As an alternative to the `Skip' button, pressing these keys will
     skip a dialing entry if the dialing function is currently active.

@{b}Abort ARexx command@{ub}
     An ARexx script started from within `term' can be aborted by
     pressing these keys. Use this function only if pressing @{b}Control +
     C@{ub} does not stop the program execution.

@{b}Commodity priority@{ub}
     The commodity priority to assign this task to. You may want to
     change this value if you have more than one program running which
     uses the same key sequences as `term'. The program with the higher
     commodity priority will receive the keystrokes first.

@{b}Hotkeys enabled@{ub}
     Whether the hotkeys are enabled or not can be toggled by clicking
     on this button, or by using the @{b}Exchange@{ub} program to be found in the
     @{b}Tools/Commodities@{ub} drawer.

@{b}Load@{ub}
     Loads the hotkey settings from a file.

@{b}Save@{ub}
     Saves the hotkey settings to a file.

@{b}Use@{ub}
     Use the current settings.

@{b}Cancel@{ub}
     Keep the original settings.

   If any changes made here do not seem to take effect immediately, the
user has probably typed a keyword wrong (causing the entire hotkey setup
to fail). I'm sorry about this, but the current implementation of
hotkey support does not sport error checking.


@EndNode

@Node "Speech_panel" "term.guide/Speech panel"
@Next "Transfer panel"
@Prev "Hotkey panel"
@Toc "Control Panels"

@{u}Speech panel@{uu}

   If enabled, the Amiga speech synthesizer will be used to alert the
user of certain actions, such as carrier lost, connection made, etc.
This feature makes sense if `term' is running in the background where
the user cannot see what is actually happening on the main screen. By
default this feature is disabled.

       @{b}Note: speech synthesis is no longer available with Kickstart 3.0
and Workbench 2.1!@{ub}

@{b}Rate@{ub}
     Speaking speed in words per minute.

@{b}Pitch@{ub}
     The greater this value, the higher the voice appears to be
     speaking.

@{b}Frequency@{ub}
     Voice frequency in Hertz.

@{b}Volume@{ub}
     The volume of the voice.

@{b}Sex@{ub}
     Enabled female or male voice.

@{b}Speech enabled@{ub}
     Toggles the activity of the speech synthesizer.

@{b}Speak!@{ub}
     Speaks a small sample text, note that speech must be enabled for
     this function to work.

@{b}Load@{ub}
     Loads the speech settings from a file.

@{b}Save@{ub}
     Saves the speech settings to a file.

@{b}Use@{ub}
     Use the current settings.

@{b}Cancel@{ub}
     Keep the original settings.


@EndNode

@Node "Transfer_panel" "term.guide/Transfer panel"
@Next "Phonebook"
@Prev "Speech panel"
@Toc "Control panels"

@{u}Transfer panel@{uu}

   The transfer routines open an information window in which a number of
transfer parameters are displayed. Additionally, the file transfer can
be aborted by clicking either of two buttons (`Abort entire transfer'
and `Skip current file'). @{b}For most transfer protocols both buttons
(abort and skip) have the same effect.@{ub} Consult the documentation to see
if different levels of abort are supported by your favourite transfer
protocol.

   The following information is displayed in the transfer window:

@{b}Protocol@{ub}
     The name of the transfer protocol currently running.

@{b}Information@{ub}
     A list to contain error message, the names files transferred and
     miscellaneous other messages addressed to the user.

@{b}File@{ub}
     The name of the file being transferred.

@{b}Next file@{ub}
     The name of the next file to be transferred.

@{b}Space left@{ub}
     The space left on the destination device. `term' will try to
     calculate the number of blocks the file being received will take
     on the destination device and display a warning the file in
     question is probably not going to fit.

     Caution:  `term' only makes a very likely guess which may or may
     not come true. The guess may be wrong if the destination device
     happens to be a kind of ram-disk which shrinks and expands as
     memory requirements come and go. Such devices are usually 100%
     full. In most other cases you will probably be able to make room
     for the file being received before any space problem turns up.

@{b}File size@{ub}
     If available, the size of the file.

@{b}Bytes transferred@{ub}
     Number of bytes transferred yet.

@{b}Total size@{ub}
     The total size of all files to be transferred.

@{b}Total bytes transferred@{ub}
     The total number of bytes transferred yet.

@{b}Files transferred@{ub}
     The number of files transferred yet and the number of files to go.

@{b}Blocks transferred@{ub}
     Number of data blocks transferred yet.

@{b}Characters/second@{ub}
     The effective transfer speed in characters per second.

@{b}Character delay@{ub}
     The delay between two character being sent.

@{b}Packet delay@{ub}
     The delay between two packets being sent.

@{b}Packet type@{ub}
     A short description of the data block type employed for data
     transfer.

@{b}Block check type@{ub}
     The method employed to verify the integrity of the data blocks
     being transferred (this usually is a form of cyclic redundancy
     checking).

@{b}Block size@{ub}
     Size of a data block in bytes.

@{b}Expected time@{ub}
     The time the transfer protocol expects the transfer will take.

@{b}Elapsed time@{ub}
     The time elapsed during transfer.

@{b}Message@{ub}
     A message of the transfer protocol addressed to the user.

@{b}Number of errors@{ub}
     The number of errors occured during file transfer.

@{b}Number of timeouts@{ub}
     The number of timeouts occured during file transfer.

   If the currently active transfer protocol provides the necessary
information, two bars will be displayed at the bottom of the transfer
window indicating the amount of transferred data and of time to go
before the transfer is finished.

   `term' knows about the Z-Modem data-inquire sequence the remote
receiver issues when expecting files. If recognized, this sequence will
cause `term' to display a requester asking for the type of data upload:
 text or binary. One could call this feature `auto upload'. You also
have the opportunity to select `Abort' which will transfer the ZModem
abort sequence or to click on the `Ignore' gadget which will plainly
ignore the fact that the ZModem inquiry sequence has been recognized.
@{b}The Z-Modem abort sequence will also be transferred if you select
the `Cancel' button in the file requester to appear after selecting
text- or binary-upload.@{ub}

       @{b}Some transfer protocols will allow you to enter a default receive
path the library is supposed to create files it receives in. On request
(see @{"Miscellaneous panel" Link "Miscellaneous_panel"}) `term' will ignore these settings and use the
settings to be changed in the `Settings/Paths' (see @{"Path panel" Link "Path_panel"}) menu
instead.@{ub}

   Each file that is received and which does not remain empty is
examined briefly to find out about the file type. If recognized
successfully and the corresponding feature is enabled, a small comment
indicating the file type will be attached to the file. `term' currently
knows about 83 different file types.

   If the `term' main window is opened on the Workbench screen, you can
select and drag icons on it in order to upload the corresponding files.
A requester will be opened to ask for the upload style (either binary or
text).

   In case a file transfer terminates with an unrecoverable error
(@{b}note:  the transfer protocol is responsible for reporting error
conditions to `term'@{ub}) the file transfer window will stay open until
explicitly closed by the user so the transfer error report list can be
viewed.


@EndNode

@Node "Phonebook" "term.guide/Phonebook"
@Next "Rate panel"
@Prev "Transfer panel"
@Toc "Control panels"

@{u}Phonebook@{uu}

   The functions described in the following can be found in the `Modem'
menu and relate to the menu entries `Phonebook', `Dial' and `Redial'.

   `term' is equipped with a telephone number management system, the
phonebook, which is described in the following lines.

@{b}Name list@{ub}
     The names of all phonebook entries are displayed here.

@{b}BBS name@{ub}
     Name of the last selected telephone book entry.

@{b}Comment@{ub}
     A comment to associate with a phonebook entry.

@{b}Phone number@{ub}
     The telephone number of the last selected telephone book entry.

     If a BBS supports multiple lines, the phone number of each line
     may be entered, each one separated by a vertical bar @{b}|@{ub} character
     (example: @{b}123456|654321@{ub} would cause the dialing routine to dial
     the numbers @{b}123456@{ub} and @{b}654321@{ub}). The dialing routine will process
     all these phone numbers before proceeding to the next phonebook
     entry.

     The @{b}|@{ub} character also works for the modem init, modem exit and dial
     prefix sequences. Whenever the dialing routine dials another phone
     number from a list separated by bars, it will try to find a
     matching init/exit/dial prefix sequence. If more phone numbers are
     specified than sequences are available, it will use the last
     sequence given (an example:  a phone number may be given as
     @{b}123456|654321|12345@{ub}, the dial prefix string may be @{b}ATDP|ATDT@{ub};
     the dialing routine will call the first number using @{b}ATDP123456@{ub},
     the second number using @{b}ATDT654321@{ub} and the third number, since no
     special dial prefix is available, again using @{b}ATDT12345@{ub}).

@{b}New entry@{ub}
     Generates a new telephone book entry with standard settings and
     places it at the end of the telephone book.

@{b}Clone entry@{ub}
     Will duplicate the currently selected phonebook entry and place it
     at the end of the list.

@{b}Remove entry@{ub}
     Removes the last selected telephone book entry from the telephone
     book and frees the memory allocated for this entry.

@{b}Dial list@{ub}
     Will pass the list of currently marked phonebook entries to the
     dialing routine.

@{b}Clear list@{ub}
     Will clear the marks set for each telephone entry in the dialing
     list.

@{b}Use entry@{ub}
     Takes over the local configuration settings saved with the
     currently selected phone book entry. Also installed are the
     associated password and user name entries.

@{b}Load list@{ub}
     Loads the contents of a telephone book from a file.

@{b}Sort list@{ub}
     If any phonebook entries have been selected to be dialed, the
     phonebook entries will be sorted in the order of dialing. The
     remaining phonebook entries will be sorted in ascending
     alphabetical order.

@{b}Save list@{ub}
     Saves the contents of a telephone book to a file.

@{b}Copy config@{ub}
     A lot of time can be saved by copying selected parts of the global
     configuration to a local configuration which is part of a phonebook
     entry. Selecting this button will invoke a control panel which
     allows to select which parts of the global configuration should be
     copied. The control panel also remembers which parts were copied
     when it was invoked the last time, see @{"Copy panel" Link "Copy_panel"} for more
     information.

@{b}Password@{ub}
     Press this button if you wish to save a special access password
     with the currently active telephone book file. You will then be
     asked to enter the password. What you type will not appear on the
     screen.

     To clear an existant password and to save the phonebook file
     without encryption, just press return when asked to enter the new
     password.

     The next time you save the phonebook data, the password will be
     encrypted and saved with it, the phonebook data itself will be
     encrypted using the password.

         @{b}Whenever an encrypted phonebook file is loaded, it will take
     longer to load than an ordinary phonebook file, the same applies to
     saving phonebook data.@{ub}

@{b}Print@{ub}
     This button will cause another control panel window to be opened
     which is to be described under @{"Printing panel" Link "Printing_panel"}.

     Another list is located at the right hand side of the window. Each
     entry refers to a control panel to be invoked on the currently
     selected phonebook entry.

@{b}Settings@{ub}
    @{b}Serial@{ub}
    @{b}Modem@{ub}
    @{b}Screen@{ub}
    @{b}Terminal@{ub}
    @{b}Emulation@{ub}
    @{b}Clipboard@{ub}
    @{b}Capture@{ub}
    @{b}Commands@{ub}
    @{b}Misc@{ub}
    @{b}Paths@{ub}
    @{b}Transfer@{ub}
    @{b}Translations@{ub}
    @{b}Function keys@{ub}
    @{b}Cursor keys@{ub}
    @{b}Fast! macros@{ub}
          These entries refer directly to the settings main menu
          entries of the same name.

    @{b}User/Password@{ub}
          This entry will open a control panel in which the password
          and user name to be used for the current phonebook entry can
          be entered. Both password and name are made available from
          within the `term' ARexx interface to allow auto login script
          files to set up a connection.

    @{b}Rates@{ub}
          `term' will count the minutes you are online and connected to
          a BBS as soon as a connection is made through the dialing
          routine. This entry opens a control panel which allows
          setting the necessary data (see @{"Rate panel" Link "Rate_panel"}).

   If you are still online, the `Dial list' gadget will be disabled. In
order to make another call hang up the line first.

   To put a phonebook entry into the dialing list, Shift-click (i.e.
hold down either shift key, then click once on the list entry) its
name. The number appearing to the left of its name indicates the
precedence of entries in the dialing list. To remove an entry from the
list, Shift-click it again. Instead of Shift-clicking on an entry, the
space bar may be pressed as well.

   Double-clicking on a name will immediately dial the selected entry.

   To dial the list of selected entries, press the `Dial list' button,
control will be passed over to the dialing panel.

   As I have been asked several times:  For dialing a telephone number
the dialing prefix specified for this telephone number is used. If the
MNP-error correction for a certain mailbox has to be specifically
switched on via the dial string, this has to be done in the modem
settings for this mailbox and not in the global settings of `term'. The
`Modem init string' and `Modem exit string' entries of the telephone
book can also be used for initialisation.


@EndNode

@Node "Rate_panel" "term.guide/Rate panel"
@Next "Copy panel"
@Prev "Phonebook"
@Toc "Control panels"

@{u}Rate panel@{uu}

   `term' will count the minutes you are online and connected to a BBS
as soon as a connection is made through the dialing routine. As soon as
the connection is lost or you hang up, `term' will use the information
to be specified in this control panel to calculate the amount of money
to be paid for the call.

@{b}Pay/unit@{ub}
     The amount of money to be paid for each single time unit when
     online. This fee must be given in the smallest currency unit
     available (pence, cents, centimes, etc.).

@{b}Seconds/unit@{ub}
     This is where you enter how many seconds each time unit lasts.

   There are two different groups of the two entries listed above
available:  one for the first unit and one for all following units. So,
if you only pay for the call you make but not for the time you spend
making it, just enter the fee in the first group and set the second
group to zero.

@{b}Days and dates@{ub}
     This list contains the default rate settings and exceptions for
     certain dates and days of the week. Each line displays the type of
     the entry and a comment (separated by the `>>' character). The
     following types are available:

    @{b}Day(s)@{ub}
          Settings for certain days of the week

    @{b}12. Jan (example)@{ub}
          Settings for a specific date

     If there is no special type available for an entry, it's probably
     the default settings you are dealing with. These settings are used
     whenever `term' cannot find an entry for the current day.

   For each entry in this list there is at least one associated starting
time available which defines when the associated rate settings are to be
used. You will find the time settings in the list titled `Time'. To add
a new time use the `Add time' button, to edit an existing entry, use
the `Edit time' button. To remove an entry, press the `Remove time'
button.

@{b}Add date@{ub}
     Will invoke a control panel to create a new rate entry to be used
     on a specific date. Use the sliders and button to select the day
     the settings will be valid for.

         @{b}The control panel will allow you to enter nonexistant dates,
     such as `31. Feb' so you will have to make sure that the date in
     question really exists.@{ub}

@{b}Add day(s)@{ub}
     Will create a new rate entry referring to one or more days of the
     week. Use the buttons of the control panel to select the days the
     current settings will be valid for.

@{b}Import@{ub}
     Much work can be saved if the rate settings for the current
     phonebook entry are imported (or copied) from a different
     phonebook entry. To do so, select this button. The control panel
     to be opened will display the list of phonebook entries available
     and three buttons:

    @{b}Replace rates@{ub}
          The rate settings of the current phonebook entry will be
          replaced by the settings of the selected entry.

    @{b}Append rates@{ub}
          The rate settings of the selected entry will be appended to
          the current phonebook entry.

    @{b}Cancel@{ub}
          Will abort the selection.

   Whenever a rate entry is selected, the corresponding parameters
(`Pay/unit' and `Seconds/unit') can be edited. If the entry refers to a
certain date or a specific day of week three additional buttons are made
available:

@{b}Edit@{ub}
     Just as the labels says, will allow you to modify an entry after
     it has been created.

@{b}Clone@{ub}
     Will duplicate the current rate entry and append it to the list.

@{b}Remove@{ub}
     Removes an entry from the list.


@EndNode

@Node "Copy_panel" "term.guide/Copy panel"
@Next "Dial panel"
@Prev "Rate panel"
@Toc "Control panels"

@{u}Copy panel@{uu}

   This control panel allows you to select which parts of the global
configuration to copy into the currently selected phonebook entry.

@{b}All@{ub}
     Selects all parts.

@{b}Clear@{ub}
     Clears the current selection.

@{b}Copy to all@{ub}
     The selected parts will be copied to all phone book entries. If any
     phone book entries are selected when this action is to be
     performed, only the selected entries will be affected.

@{b}Copy@{ub}
     This is where you select from which source the configuration
     information will be copied:

    @{b}Global configuration@{ub}
          Parts of the currently active global configuration will be
          copied.

    @{b}Defaults@{ub}
          When going online, instead of overriding the currently active
          global configuration with the supplied local phone book
          configuration the corresponding global configuration will be
          left unchanged.


@EndNode

@Node "Dial_panel" "term.guide/Dial panel"
@Next "Printing panel"
@Prev "Copy panel"
@Toc "Control panels"

@{u}Dial panel@{uu}

   The following information about the dialing process is displayed:

@{b}Calling@{ub}
     The name of the telephone book entry belonging to the number being
     dialled. If it is just a telephone number the string @{b}-- Unknown --@{ub}
     is shown, meaning that the name of the mailbox is unknown.

@{b}Comment@{ub}
     This is where the comment corresponding to the current dialing list
     entry is displayed.

@{b}Number@{ub}
     The telephone number being dialed or just dialed.

@{b}Next@{ub}
     The name of the telephone book entry which will be processed next
     if no connection is established. If no further entry exists, @{b}--
     None --@{ub} will be displayed.

@{b}Timeout@{ub}
     A counter which is decreased every second and which reflects the
     time remaining to establish a connection or to cycle through the
     dial queue again.

@{b}Attempt@{ub}
     This field shows the number of unsuccessful cycles made through the
     dialing queue to establish a connection.

@{b}Message@{ub}
     A message to the user. This can be:

    @{b}Dialing...@{ub}
          A dial is in process.

    @{b}Line is busy.@{ub}
          The dialed number is engaged.

    @{b}Incoming call!@{ub}
          The modem has been called from another modem.

    @{b}Incoming voice call!@{ub}
          The modem is receiving a call which was not originated by
          another modem.

    @{b}No dialtone detected!@{ub}
          The modem was unable to detect any dialing tone on the line,
          it may possibly be not connected.

    @{b}Connection established.@{ub}
          Just as the name says...

    @{b}Maximum number of dial retries reached!@{ub}
          Just as the name says...

    @{b}Dial attempt timeout.@{ub}
          The time available to establish a connection has been reached
          or exceeded.

    @{b}Redial Delay...@{ub}
          Pause until the next cycle through the dialing queue.

   Additionally three buttons can be found in the input field which
initiate the following functions.

@{b}Skip call@{ub}
     With this function the current dialing attempt is cancelled and
     the next number is processed. If no succeeding telephone number
     exists `term' waits for the next cycle through the dial queue or
     until `Skip call' is pressed again.

     There also is a hotkey combination available to accomplish the same
     effect.

@{b}Remove@{ub}
     This button works in part similar to the `Skip call' button.
     Additionally, it removes the current phonebook entry from the
     dialing list.

@{b}Go to online@{ub}
     If the line is very noisy, the connection to a mailbox has been
     made but the @{b}CONNECT@{ub} signal has been lost, you can use this button
     to switch directly to the online mode of the modem. This will also
     start the pay unit counter and the dial queue will be exited.

@{b}Abort dialing@{ub}
     Operation of this button exits the dial queue (leaving the the dial
     queue intact) and ends the dialing process.

   If a connection is successfully made the corresponding entry in the
dial queue will be removed.

   Selecting the close gadget will close the window and cause the phone
book panel to be reopened.


@EndNode

@Node "Printing_panel" "term.guide/Printing panel"
@Prev "Dial panel"
@Toc "Control panels"

@{u}Printing panel@{uu}

   This control panel is part of the phone book. It is opened whenever
the @{b}Print@{ub} button is selected and allows for setting the output options.

@{b}Output file or device@{ub}
     This is where you enter the name of the file or device (such as
     @{b}PRT:@{ub}) the phonebook printout is to be sent to.

@{b}Plain text@{ub}
     If enabled only the plain and bare information text will be
     printed, else text attribute control sequences will be sent as
     well.

@{b}Include...@{ub}
     Each switch determines whether the corresponding phonebook entry
     information will be included in the printout.

@{b}Use@{ub}
     Will start printing the phonebook contents.

@{b}Cancel@{ub}
     Returns to the phonebook.


@EndNode

@Node "Text_buffer" "term.guide/Text buffer"
@Next "Clipboard"
@Prev "Control panels"
@Toc "Main"

@{u}@{b}Text buffer@{uu}@{ub}

   The text buffer is a function which continually stores text
displayed on `term's main screen, so that the user can inform himself
about the received text at any time.


 @{" General characteristics " Link "General_characteristics"}  General information on the text buffer.
 @{" Operation " Link "Operation"}                How to operate the text buffer?


@EndNode

@Node "General_characteristics" "term.guide/General characteristics"
@Next "Operation"
@Prev "Text buffer"
@Toc "Text buffer"

@{u}General characteristics@{uu}

   The size of the text buffer is managed dynamically so that for every
new line which is read new memory must be allocated. So the size of the
text buffer is limited only by the amount of the available memory. It
is recommended that the text buffer is emptied periodically to avoid
using the entire free memory.

   If there is insufficient memory to place a new line into the text
buffer, the first line will be deleted to make room for the new line.


@EndNode

@Node "Operation" "term.guide/Operation"
@Prev "General characteristics"
@Toc "Text buffer"

@{u}Operation@{uu}

   The contents of the text buffer can be paged through using the keys
for moving of the cursor (@{b}Shift + Cursor@{ub} keys moves page by page,
@{b}Control + Cursor@{ub} key jumps to the beginning or end of the text
buffer). Additionally, the numeric keypad keys are overlaid with jump
and paging functions (corresponding to the inscriptions/graphics on the
front of the keys).

   Additionally there is another menu whose functions should be
explained briefly:

@{b}Search@{ub}
     A search function is called which searches from the topmost line
     on the screen downwards for an entered search string. Upper- and
     lowercase are ignored by this function. If the search string is
     found it is displayed and highlighted.

@{b}Repeat search@{ub}
     Continues the search process started with `Search'. The previously
     entered search string is carried over.

@{b}Go to main screen@{ub}
     Switches to the main screen of `term'.

@{b}Clear buffer@{ub}
     Clears the contents of the @{"Text buffer" Link "Text_buffer"}.

@{b}Close buffer, Quit@{ub}
     Closes the @{"Text buffer" Link "Text_buffer"} screen but leaves the contents unchanged.


@EndNode

@Node "Clipboard" "term.guide/Clipboard"
@Next "Command sequences"
@Prev "Text buffer"
@Toc "Main"

@{u}@{b}Clipboard@{uu}@{ub}

   Cut & paste functions are available on the main screen, the buffer
screen and the review buffer. Here is how to use them:

@{b}Buffer screen@{ub}
     Use the mouse to point to the first character you wish to send to
     the clipboard, hold down the select button, drag the mouse to the
     last character you wish to copy and release the button. The text
     marked will be transferred to the clipboard.

     Holding down the @{b}Control@{ub} key while clicking on a character will
     feed the single character into the input stream, it will not be
     buffered in the clipboard.

@{b}Main screen@{ub}
     Use the mouse to point to the first character you wish to send to
     the clipboard, hold down the select button, drag the mouse to the
     last character you wish to select and release the button. Select
     the `Copy' menu item (see @{"Edit" Link "Edit"} menu) to transfer the text to the
     clipboard. Instead of dragging the mouse you may also double-click
     on a single word to select it.

     Holding down the @{b}Control@{ub} key while clicking on a character will
     feed the single character into the input stream, it will not be
     buffered in the clipboard.

@{b}Review buffer@{ub}
     Use the mouse to point to the first character you wish to send to
     the clipboard, hold down the select button, drag the mouse to the
     last character you wish to select and release the button. Press
     @{b}Amiga + C@{ub} to copy the selected text to the clipboard.

   To paste the clipboard contents, i.e. feed them into the terminal
input stream, either select the `Paste' menu item (see @{"Edit" Link "Edit"} menu) or
press @{b}Amiga + V@{ub}. In order to send the clipboard contents along with a
@{b}Paste prefix@{ub} and @{b}Paste suffix@{ub} hold down any @{b}Shift@{ub} key when
selecting the @{b}Paste@{ub} menu entry or when selecting text with the mouse
(this works both with the main screen and the @{"Text buffer" Link "Text_buffer"} screen).

   Hold down one of the @{b}Alt@{ub} keys and press the left mouse button to
make `term' emit a number of cursor move sequences which will position
the on-screen cursor at the spot where you clicked the mouse.

   In standard string editing gadgets a solution had to be found to
preserve the line editing functions while still supporting menu
shortcuts. To undo any changes made press @{b}Amiga + Q@{ub}, to clear the
string editing gadgets press @{b}Amiga + X@{ub}. Menus associated with the
shortcuts @{b}Amiga + Q/X@{ub} are called by holding down any @{b}Shift@{ub} key along
with the @{b}Amiga@{ub} keys (i.e. @{b}Shift + Amiga + Q@{ub} will select the `Quit' menu
item if available).

   Clipboard functions are also available within string gadgets:  press
@{b}Amiga + C@{ub} to copy the contents of the gadget to the clipboard and
press @{b}Amiga + V@{ub} to insert the current clipboard contents at the current
cursor position.


@EndNode

@Node "Command_sequences" "term.guide/Command sequences"
@Next "Fast! macros"
@Prev "Clipboard"
@Toc "Main"

@{u}@{b}Command sequences@{uu}@{ub}

   Each string sent directly to the modem is a command sequence. This
includes telephone numbers, modem initialisation strings, function key
assignments, etc. In addition to the normal text strings various other
commands are supported which will be described in the following section.


 @{" Backslash " Link "Backslash"}  The backslash @{b}\@{ub}
 @{" Caret " Link "Caret"}      The caret @{b}^@{ub}
 @{" Tilde " Link "Tilde"}      The tilde @{b}~@{ub}


@EndNode

@Node "Backslash" "term.guide/Backslash"
@Next "Caret"
@Prev "Command sequences"
@Toc "Command sequences"

@{u}Backslash@{uu}

@{b}\\@{ub}
     Generates a single backslash.

@{b}\a@{ub}
     Executes an ARexx command (all text to follow this character).

@{b}\b@{ub}
     Generates a backspace (deletes the character to the left of the
     cursor).

@{b}\c@{ub}
     Calls a main menu entry, the menu entry to be called is determined
     by the argument to follow; this is either a six digit number
     (example: @{b}\c 010203@{ub} would call subitem 1, item 2, menu 3) or the
     name of the menu entry enclosed in single quotes to call (example:
     @{b}\c 'about'@{ub} would call the `About...' menu entry, the search is
     case-insensitive and only compares the characters given).

@{b}\d@{ub}
     Executes an AmigaDOS command (all text to follow this character).

@{b}\e@{ub}
     Generates the escape character (ASCII code 27).

@{b}\f@{ub}
     Generates a form feed (skip to beginning of the next page or clear
     the screen).

@{b}\g@{ub}
     Places the string to follow this character in the clipboard.

@{b}\i@{ub}
     Feeds the contents of the clipboard into the input stream.

@{b}\n@{ub}
     Generates a line feed.

@{b}\p@{ub}
     Feeds the password of the telephone book entry into the input
     stream of the last made connection. @{b}The password is automatically
     cleared for security reasons when the connection is broken.@{ub}

@{b}\r@{ub}
     Generates a carriage return.

@{b}\t@{ub}
     Generates a tab jump.

@{b}\u@{ub}
     Similar to the @{b}\p@{ub} command, the @{b}\u@{ub} command will feed the current
     user name into the input stream.

@{b}\x@{ub}
     Generates a break signal (as with the `Send break' menu entry).

@{b}\^@{ub}
     Generates a caret character.

@{b}\*@{ub}
     The code to follow the asterisk determines the character to
     produce. This can be any three digit number or a symbolic name
     from the following list (1):

         @{b}NUL@{ub}, @{b}SOH@{ub}, @{b}STX@{ub}, @{b}ETX@{ub}, @{b}EOT@{ub}, @{b}ENQ@{ub}, @{b}ACK@{ub}, @{b}BEL@{ub}, @{b}BS@{ub}, @{b}HT@{ub}, @{b}LF@{ub}, @{b}VT@{ub}, @{b}FF@{ub},
     @{b}CR@{ub}, @{b}SO@{ub}, @{b}SI@{ub}, @{b}DLE@{ub}, @{b}DC1@{ub}, @{b}DC2@{ub}, @{b}DC3@{ub}, @{b}DC4@{ub}, @{b}NAK@{ub}, @{b}SYN@{ub}, @{b}ETB@{ub}, @{b}CAN@{ub},
     @{b}EM@{ub}, @{b}SUB@{ub}, @{b}ESC@{ub}, @{b}FS@{ub}, @{b}GS@{ub}, @{b}RS@{ub}, @{b}US@{ub}, @{b}SP@{ub}, @{b}DEL@{ub}, @{b}SS2@{ub}, @{b}SS3@{ub}, @{b}DCS@{ub}, @{b}CSI@{ub}, @{b}ST@{ub},
     @{b}OSC@{ub}, @{b}PM@{ub}, @{b}APC@{ub}, @{b}NBS@{ub} and @{b}SHY@{ub}

   If none of the mentioned combinations is recognized the character
which follows the @{b}\@{ub} will be fed into the input stream without any
changes.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  @{b}EOU@{ub} may be implemented in a future release


@EndNode

@Node "Caret" "term.guide/Caret"
@Next "Tilde"
@Prev "Backslash"
@Toc "Command sequences"

@{u}Caret@{uu}

   This character is used to change the following character to a
`control character'. So the sequence @{b}^J@{ub} will become a Line feed and @{b}^I@{ub}
becomes a tab jump. The character which follows the @{b}^@{ub} has to be located
between @{b}@@{ub} and @{b}[@{ub}, otherwise it is fed into the input stream without
changes.


@EndNode

@Node "Tilde" "term.guide/Tilde"
@Prev "Caret"
@Toc "Command sequences"

@{u}Tilde@{uu}

   This character causes the program to pause for exactly half a second
before it continues to process the following commands.


@EndNode

@Node "Fast!_macros" "term.guide/Fast! macros"
@Next "Packet window"
@Prev "Command sequences"
@Toc "Main"

@{u}@{b}Fast! macros@{uu}@{ub}

   In implementation and design the fast! macros are closely related to
the function key macros (see @{"Function key panel" Link "Function_key_panel"}). If invoked by
selecting the corresponding menu entry, a window will open on the right
hand side of the screen sporting a scrollable list of macros (the
contents of this list can be edited using the @{"Fast macro panel" Link "Fast_macro_panel"}). When a
list entry is selected, the associated command sequence (see
@{"Command sequences" Link "Command_sequences"}) will be executed.

   By using the fast! macros it is theoretically possible to control a
BBS just by mouse, provided that you have the approriate macros in your
fast! macro list.

   The fast! macro panel can be resized and acts just like the main
`term' window:  menu items can be selected and characters entered are
sent to the serial driver.


@EndNode

@Node "Packet_window" "term.guide/Packet window"
@Next "Environment variables"
@Prev "Fast! macros"
@Toc "Main"

@{u}@{b}Packet window@{uu}@{ub}

   In this window a line can be edited before it is sent. All the usual
editing functions known from standard input fields are available (@{b}Shift
+ cursor left/right@{ub} jumps to the start/end of the line).

   Additionally, some extended functions exist which are performed by
pressing a cursor key together with the @{b}Shift@{ub} or @{b}Control@{ub} key:

@{b}Control + Cursor left@{ub}
     Jumps to the next word.

@{b}Control + Cursor right@{ub}
     Jumps to the previous word.

@{b}Cursor up@{ub}
     Shows the last entered command in the input line.

@{b}Shift + Cursor up@{ub}
     Shows the very first command entered so far.

@{b}Cursor down@{ub}
     Shows the next entered command (if you moved back for some
     commands before).

@{b}Shift + Cursor down@{ub}
     Shows the very last command entered so far.

   This string gadget has a buffer where all previously entered commands
are stored (`Command history'). You can page through this buffer, load
and save it and individual lines can be recalled. As with the
@{"Text buffer" Link "Text_buffer"} this buffer is managed dynamically. The same memory
restrictions that apply to the @{"Text buffer" Link "Text_buffer"} are valid for this buffer.

   The input line also has a menu which offers the following functions:

@{b}Load history@{ub}
     Loads the contents of the input line buffer from a file. Each
     stored line in this file can be recalled and sent.

@{b}Save history as...@{ub}
     Saves the contents of the input line buffer to a file.

@{b}Clear history@{ub}
     Simply releases all previously stored commands and the memory used
     by them.

@{b}Other window@{ub}
     Switches to the main screen of `term'.

@{b}Quit@{ub}
     Closes the window (corresponds to clicking the close gadget of the
     window).

       @{b}Every character entered into this window is shown immediately so
that those things where it is better that they should not appear on the
screen (like passwords for a mailbox) should be entered in another way.@{ub}

   The content of every input line is interpreted as a command sequence
and therefore can also contain control characters.

   If a line taken from the input buffer is sent without change it is
@{b}not@{ub} stored in the buffer again (`true history' as known from
`ConMan').

   The contents of the input buffer are cleared automatically after the
window is closed. @{b}Under no circumstances are the contents maintained
until the next call!@{ub}

   Provided that the packet window is large enough, a list to contain
the command line history will be displayed.


@EndNode

@Node "Environment_variables" "term.guide/Environment variables"
@Next "Gift-Ware fee"
@Prev "Packet window"
@Toc "Main"

@{u}@{b}Environment variables@{uu}@{ub}

   Information which is to be available the next time the program is
run is placed as AmigaDOS variables in the directory @{b}ENV:@{ub} and @{b}ENVARC:@{ub}
by `term'.

   The variables used by `term' can be used and manipulated by other
programs transparently. In detail these variables are:

@{b}TERMCONFIGPATH@{ub}
     The name of the directory in which all information used by `term'
     is placed (standard configuration, telephone book, etc.). The
     default settings file name is @{b}ENVARC:term@{ub}.

@{b}TERMWINDOW@{ub}
     The window definition which can also be entered in the program via
     the menu item @{"Settings" Link "Settings"}.

@{b}xpr...@{ub}
     The standard settings used for the corresponding transfer protocol
     (@{b}xprzmodem@{ub}, @{b}xprkermit@{ub}, etc.).

@{b}xem...@{ub}
     The standard settings used for the corresponding external terminal
     emulation library (@{b}xemvt340@{ub}, @{b}xemascii@{ub}, etc.).


@EndNode

@Node "Gift-Ware_fee" "term.guide/Gift-Ware fee"
@Next "Index"
@Prev "Environment variables"
@Toc "Main"

@{u}@{b}Gift-Ware fee@{uu}@{ub}

   The development of `term' required considerable expense. The effort
to find out by trial and error and with a little help from the
DevCon-Disks and the Includes & Autodocs the operating principles of
some routines would alone be worth a remuneration to the author (it's
simply bad luck if the Atlanta-DevCon records arrive with considerable
delay). The author is susceptible to all kinds of donation and gifts so
long as it is assured that they are useful to him (these nice little
sacks with elephant food are better sent to the Hanover zoo). Therefore
anyone pleased by `term' or who works with the source code is welcome to
remunerate my programming efforts as he/she thinks that it matches my
efforts - a lot of thanks! If you have got no ideas yet, here is a (by
no means complete) list:

   ñ Old CinemaWare games -- with the exception of @{i}Defender of the
     Crown@{ui}, @{i}The King of Chicago@{ui}, @{i}Sinbad@{ui}, @{i}It came from the desert@{ui}
     @{i}TV-Sports Basketball@{ui} and @{i}TV-Sports Football@{ui}

   ñ Old Activision, Electronic Arts and Epyx games

   ñ Scenery disks for the SubLogic Flight-Simulator II -- except for
     @{i}Japan@{ui} and @{i}USA #9@{ui}

   ñ The films @{i}The meaning of life@{ui}, @{i}Jabberwocky@{ui}, @{i}Brazil@{ui}, @{i}The Fisher
     King@{ui} or @{i}Time Bandits@{ui} on a PAL-VHS video cassette

   ñ A CD by the Beatles, Jackson Browne, Weather Report, Paul Simon
     (1971-1985), Eric Clapton (-1988), Al DiMeola (1977-)

   ñ A CD by Steely Dan (@{i}Can't buy a thrill@{ui}, @{i}The early years@{ui}, @{i}Berry
     Town@{ui}, @{i}Old regime@{ui}, @{i}Stone piano@{ui}, @{i}You go where I go@{ui}, @{i}Founders of
     Steely Dan@{ui}, @{i}Sun Mountain@{ui}) or by Donald Fagen (@{i}The Nightfly@{ui}, @{i}The
     New York Rock & Soul Revue@{ui}, @{i}Teahouse on the tracks@{ui})

   ñ A book by Michael Crichton, Bruce Chatwin or Steven Meretzky

                              My address:

                             Olaf Barthel
                           Brabeckstrasse 35
                          D-3000 Hannover 71

                      Federal Republic of Germany

                 Internet: olsen@sourcery.mxm.sub.org

   Would those people looking at the source code to extend it or do some
modifications here and there please contact me before publication so
that our efforts can be coordinated.


@EndNode

